insert into quests (day_number, title, subtitle, description, tier, xp_value, is_boss) values
(1, 'Hello, World!', 'Start here', 'Python is an interpreted language. That means it does not wait until the entire program is finished before doing work. Instead, it reads and executes code line by line, in the order you wrote it. Order matters, because a later line can only use values that were created earlier. The first tool we learn is print. print is the simplest way to tell Python to display something on the screen, but it is much more important than it first appears. Programmers use print to confirm what a script is doing, to check the result of a calculation, to display the state of an object, or to show whether a task finished successfully. For example, a script might say Finished when everything worked, or Unfinished when it did not. Today your job is to write a program that prints Hello World so you can see the full loop from code to output.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(2, 'Print with purpose', 'Show output clearly', 'Print is not only for showing a message to a person. It is one of the easiest ways to inspect what your program knows at a moment in time. If a variable has the wrong value, print can reveal it. If a function returned something unexpected, print can help you find out where the problem started. This lesson expands on that idea by having you print several messages and observe how output changes with each line.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(3, 'Variables', 'Store values', 'A variable gives a name to a value. That matters because code becomes much easier to read when you can say player_name instead of repeating the same text everywhere. Variables also let programs change over time. A score can start at 0, increase after each correct answer, and then be shown at the end. In this quest, you will practice assigning values and reusing them so the idea becomes natural.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(4, 'Input basics', 'Talk to the user', 'Programs become interactive when they can respond to the person using them. input pauses the program and waits for typed text, then returns that text so your code can use it. This is how you ask questions, collect names, get choices, and build conversations. In game terms, input is how the code hears the player. Today you will use it to let your program react to what someone types.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(5, 'Numbers and math', 'Work with values', 'Numbers are the building blocks of calculations. Python can add, subtract, multiply, divide, and compare them, but it does so as real data, not as text. That difference matters because a score should act like a number, not a string of characters. If you accidentally treat numbers like text, the program behaves differently. This lesson helps you see why numeric types are separate and how that powers counters, totals, and game logic.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(6, 'Strings', 'Text matters', 'Strings are sequences of characters, and they are how Python represents words, sentences, names, and dialogue. They are essential because most user-facing parts of a program are text. You will learn how strings are created, combined, and displayed, and why text handling becomes important in menus, prompts, and character creation. By the end of this quest, strings should feel like the language your program uses to speak.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(7, 'Mini challenge 1', 'First checkpoint', 'The first checkpoint is a small review of the ideas you have learned so far. Instead of treating print, input, and variables as separate tricks, use them together in a simple program that asks for something, stores it, and shows a result. The point is to understand how these pieces form a basic interactive script. This is where the system starts to feel like a real tool instead of isolated exercises.', 'boss', 100, true),
(8, 'Lists', 'Store many items', 'A list is a container for multiple values in a specific order. That matters whenever one idea is not enough, such as a set of choices, items in an inventory, or steps in a checklist. Lists let you keep related things together, loop over them, and change them as a group. This quest shows why lists are the right choice when your program needs to remember more than one thing.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(9, 'If statements', 'Make choices', 'If statements give Python decision-making ability. They let code take one path when a condition is true and another path when it is false. That is how programs become responsive instead of fixed. A quiz can mark answers right or wrong, a game can unlock a door only with a key, and a script can choose different messages based on the result. This lesson focuses on how branches work and why conditions are such an important part of logic.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(10, 'Loops', 'Repeat with control', 'Loops solve the problem of repetition. If you need something to happen many times, writing the same line again and again is tedious and error-prone. A loop lets you say, “do this for each item” or “repeat until this changes.” This quest explains why repetition is one of the most common patterns in programming and how loops keep your code compact and flexible.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(11, 'While loops', 'Keep going until done', 'A while loop keeps running until the condition becomes false. That makes it useful when you do not know the exact number of repetitions ahead of time. For example, a program might keep asking for input until the user enters the correct answer. The lesson here is not just syntax, but the idea of continuing work until a goal is reached.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(12, 'Dictionaries', 'Label your data', 'Dictionaries store values under meaningful keys. Instead of remembering that position 0 means name and position 1 means class, you can ask directly for the value associated with a label. That makes code easier to understand and less fragile when the structure changes. In this quest, you will see why labeled data is so useful for characters, settings, and structured information.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(13, 'Functions', 'Reuse behavior', 'Functions package behavior into a reusable block of code. They are useful because many programs need the same action in multiple places, and copying code creates clutter and bugs. With a function, you define the idea once and use it whenever needed. This lesson explains why functions are one of the biggest steps toward writing organized, maintainable programs.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(14, 'Mini challenge 2', 'Second checkpoint', 'This checkpoint combines the earlier lessons into a more complete workflow. You will use conditions, variables, and repetition together, which helps you see how programming concepts interact instead of standing alone. The goal is to build confidence in understanding the flow of a program from input to decision to output.', 'boss', 100, true),
(15, 'Debugging', 'Read the clues', 'Every programmer writes bugs. Debugging is the skill of finding out why the code did not do what you expected. Error messages are not just failures; they are clues about where to look next. This quest teaches you to read those clues carefully, test assumptions, and use evidence instead of guesswork.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(16, 'Lists in depth', 'Change collections', 'Once you know how lists work, the next step is learning how to change them. Programs often need to add items, remove items, or look through every element in a collection. This lesson helps you understand how lists behave when they grow and change over time.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(17, 'String methods', 'Shape text', 'Real programs do more than display text. They often clean it, split it apart, or transform it before using it. String methods are the tools that make that possible. This quest explains why text processing matters when dealing with user input, file data, or formatted output.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(18, 'Functions with inputs', 'Pass values in', 'A function becomes more powerful when it accepts data and returns a result. That lets you build flexible tools that work in more than one situation. Instead of hard-coding one answer, you can feed a function different values and let it compute the right result each time. This lesson focuses on why that pattern is so important.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(19, 'Files', 'Remember later', 'Files solve a major limitation of simple scripts: memory does not persist after the program closes. When a program writes to a file, it can remember data for the next time it runs. That is how saves, logs, and stored settings work. This quest explains why persistence matters and how files let your program keep information over time.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(20, 'Try and except', 'Handle mistakes safely', 'Not every problem should crash the whole program. Try and except gives you a way to attempt a risky action and recover gracefully if it fails. That is important because users make unexpected choices and data is not always perfect. The lesson here is that good software anticipates failure and handles it intentionally.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(21, 'Mini challenge 3', 'Third checkpoint', 'This checkpoint is a chance to prove that the foundational ideas now work together. Build a small quiz or scoring script and think through why each line exists. The point is to move from isolated syntax practice into real program structure.', 'boss', 100, true),
(22, 'Modules', 'Use existing tools', 'Modules let you import code someone else already wrote. That matters because no one should have to solve every problem from scratch. Python’s ecosystem works because code can be shared, reused, and trusted. This lesson introduces that idea and shows why importing tools is part of writing practical programs.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(23, 'Planning a project', 'Break it apart', 'Before writing a larger project, it helps to decide what problem you are solving and how to split it into smaller parts. Planning prevents you from getting lost in the details too early. This quest is about thinking through structure first so the build stage becomes easier and more focused.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(24, 'Classes basics', 'Model things', 'Classes let you describe an object by combining data and behavior in one place. That makes them useful for things like characters, items, enemies, and tools in a game. Instead of thinking only about individual values, you begin to think about objects that have state and actions. This lesson explains why object-oriented code is useful for building larger systems.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(25, 'Capstone helpers', 'Put pieces together', 'This quest is about integration. By now, you have learned separate concepts, but the real skill is knowing how to combine them into a useful program. This lesson pushes you to connect pieces, make design choices, and understand how the parts support the whole.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(26, 'Review day', 'Strengthen understanding', 'Review is where memorization turns into understanding. Re-explaining concepts in your own words helps you notice what you actually know and what still feels unclear. This quest reinforces the idea that learning programming is not only about syntax, but about being able to explain why the syntax exists.', 'beginner', 25, false),
(27, 'Final mini project', 'Fourth checkpoint', 'This final checkpoint asks you to build something small but complete using the tools you have learned. The important part is not just that it works, but that you understand the decisions behind it: why this value is a variable, why this part is a function, and why this branch exists. A finished project is proof that the individual lessons now fit together.', 'boss', 100, true),
(28, 'Celebrate and continue', 'You are ready', 'The final quest is a reflection on the journey. You now have the foundations needed to keep learning, reading code, and building your own ideas. The most important takeaway is that programming is not magic; it is a system of ideas that make sense when you understand the purpose behind each one.', 'beginner', 25, false)
